abstract: THE most important of June's astro- nomical happenings is the arrival of the sun at the extreme northerly point in its course. Ever since a few days before last Christmas, when it was at its furthest southerly reach, it has been Jour- neying in this direction. This movement is, of course, apparent only, being caused by the actual movement of the earth in the opposite direction.

abstract: POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y., June 2 -- Walter Greer, aged nine years, in play to-day pointed a double-barreled shotgun at his seven-year-old brother Harold, at his home, near Pleasant Valley, and when he pulled the trigger the contents of a shell were emptied into the breast of the little fellow. He lived ten minutes.

abstract: CHICAGO, June 4 -- Liquidation was the feature to-day in wheat. July, after covering a range of 4 3/8 cents, closed weak and 1 1/8 cents lower. abstract: ST. LOUIS, June 5 -- Once more the redoubtable Mathewson, phenomenal pitcher of the New York baseball team, has gone down to defeat before the hard-hitting St. Louis team. abstract: BALTIMORE, June 7. -- The market today shook off the easing tendency of yesterday, and firmed up perceptibly under the leadership of the Seaboards. abstract: BALTIMORE, June 10 -- The market to-day was exceptionally dull, due entirely to the early offishness in New York. The market lapsed into a stagnant condition the moment it was noted the Seaboard group was quiet. Though this group yielded slightly, as the result of a little ready selling by the more willing speculative crowd, there was a strong bullish sentiment, particularly on the common.

abstract: WEST BADEN, Ind., June 14 -- The Mineral Springs Hotel was destroyed by fire early to-day. No person was injured. The fire broke out at 1 A.M. It burned rapidly and by 3 o'clock the hotel had been completely consumed. The damages amount to $500,000; insurance, $100,000. The large frame structure burned so rapidly that the guests had difficulty in escaping with their lives.

abstract: This is the period of the year when flat-house burglars begin to thrive. abstract: ITHACA, N.Y., June 16 -- James Churchill, a farmhand who worked near Ithaca, early this morning murdered his wife. abstract: To the Editor of The New York Times: Last Friday's collision between the ferryboats Mauch Chunk and Northfield at South Ferry calls attention to the condition of affairs that exists there. abstract: To the Editor of The New York Times: This seems to be the age of "commissions." abstract: ROANOKE, Va., June 23 -- Much anxiety was felt here to-day on receipt of the report that a cloudburst and flood had swept over the Elkhorn coal region in West Virginia. This territory is near the Virginia line, and is about 125 miles west of Ronaoke and 25 miles west of Bluefield, West Va. The region visited by the flood is said to be devastated, and the Pocahontas coal fields are reported in ruins.

abstract: NEW HAVEN, Conn., June 29. -- Maier Zunder, one of the oldest merchants of this city died to-day of gastritis and exhaustion, induced by the heat of the last two days. abstract: MONTGOMERY, Ala., June 29. -- A suffrage and elections article for the proposed new Constitution was submitted to the Constitutional Convention to-day. It provides that, to vote at any election, a citizen shall have resided in the State at least two years, county one year, and precinct or ward three months preceding the election, and he shall have been daly registered and shall have paid all poll taxes due.

abstract: NEWPORT, June 29. -- The new Summer home of Mr. and Mrs. Edward J. Berwind. The Elms, on Bellevue Avenue, is one of the most beautiful in Newport. It is constructed of white stone in the style of Louis XIV., with a central pavilion projecting beyond the two wings. The architecture is sober and yet graceful, and the architect, Horace Trumbauer of Philadelphia, has taken care that all the details have been perfectly executed.
